description: The short answer is yes, the money did help students make up for the learning they missed during COVID. But it didn’t get them all the way there.
title: Congress poured billions of dollars into schools. Did it help students learn?

description: A U.S. Supreme Court opinion briefly posted on its website suggests the court will allow abortions in medical emergencies in Idaho, according to Bloomberg News, which obtained a copy of the opinions.
title: SCOTUS appears to post opinion allowing Idaho to offer emergency medical abortions

description: The Food and Drug Administration says more than 60 products made by Totally Cool Inc. of Owings Mills, Md., are part of the recall, including brands such as Hershey's, Friendly's, Chipwich and Jeni's.
title: More than 60 ice cream products recalled over possible listeria contamination

description: Morgan, who turns 35 in July, helped lead the U.S. to a gold medal in 2012 and World Cup titles in 2015 and 2019. But the team has since struggled, and the Olympic roster will feature younger players.
title: U.S. Soccer announces women's Olympic roster, leaving out longtime star Alex Morgan

description: President Joe Biden issued a blanket pardon on Wednesday morning to LGBTQI+ service members removed from the military because of their sexual orientation/gender identity.
title: Biden issues blanket pardon to troops expelled from the military for their sexuality

description: In Uchenna Awoke’s debut novel, we come to understand that 15-year-old Dimkpa’s choices are painfully constricted by the caste system into which he was born.
title: 'The Liquid Eye of a Moon' is a Nigerian coming-of-age story

description: Buteau says covering the news of the 2001 terrorist attacks crystalized her desire to go into comedy. She stars in the film Babes and in the Netflix series Survival of the Thickest.
title: After the Sept. 11 attacks, Michelle Buteau decided: 'I better start living'

description: The case is one element in a right-wing legal and political campaign that frames efforts to respond to false and misleading information as censorship.
title: What it means for the election that the government can talk to tech companies

description: The court by a vote of 6-3 ruled that those challenging the government’s interaction with social media companies lacked legal standing to sue.
title: Supreme Court allows White House to request removal of misinformation on social media

description: The WikiLeaks founder pleaded guilty to one count of violating espionage laws in a U.S. court in the Northern Mariana Islands, where the judge sentenced him to time served for his lengthy prison stay.
title: Assange arrives in Australia after pleading guilty to espionage on the way home

description: The FDA found Bimbo Bakeries USA — which includes brands such as Sara Lee and Ball Park buns and rolls — listed ingredients such as sesame or tree nuts on labels even when they weren't in the foods.
title: FDA warns top U.S. bakery not to claim foods contain allergens when they don't

description: After hitting a 40-year high in 2022, pedestrian deaths decreased last year to just over 7,300, according to a new report by the Governors Highway Safety Association.
title: Pedestrian deaths have fallen for the first time since the pandemic

description: A vast swath of the Midwest has been under siege from torrential rains while also being hit with a heat wave. Hundreds of people were rescued, homes were damaged, and at least two people have died.
title: Iowa floodwaters breach levees as even more rain dumps onto parts of the Midwest

description: Assange pleaded guilty to a felony charge of violating the Espionage Act. His court hearing was held in Saipan, in the Northern Mariana Islands, a U.S. commonwealth.
title: WikiLeaks founder Julian Assange is free, ending years-long legal saga
